  "response_text": "The cumulative total of postpartum female prey animals harvested by forager bands initiates at zero and climbs steadily during the early simulation phases. This initial acceleration reflects the successful targeting of this reproductive cohort. The metric exhibits a robust increasing trend for the first 1391 time steps, after which the rate of accumulation slows notably. A distinct peak is reached at approximately time step 1826 with an average value of 119. Following this maximum, the count fluctuates minimally, concluding the run at a mean of 117. The statistical profile indicates a transition from a phase of significant growth to a period of stability and eventual stasis. This plateau likely signals the depletion of the accessible postpartum female subpopulation, indicating that the foraging pressure has effectively removed this vulnerable demographic from the landscape. The consistency of this trajectory across the 40 simulation runs is supported by the low variance relative to the magnitude of the count, pointing to a deterministic outcome under these specific environmental and predation parameters."
}

